{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505065"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:25:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2401"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2401"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.66,0.02,0.1,0.09,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43264"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2401","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2401"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2401"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28254"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"8840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1691"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1855"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/43264"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a painful left eye several hours after hitting his eye when opening a cupboard door. His vision is blurred. He does not feel nauseated. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, there is some bruising of the eyelids and a hyphaema in the bottom quarter of the anterior chamber. He can move his eye freely, with no double vision or areas of numbness around the orbit. A prompt ophthalmological opinion is sought.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"In the interim, which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Eye shield","Intramuscular tropisetron","Cyclopentolate eye drops","Atropine eye drops","Timolol eye drops"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has hyphaema after a traumatic injury to the eye. In particular, it is not associated with ophthalmoplegia or sensory loss around the eye. An uncomplicated traumatic hyphaema is generally a benign condition that resolves on its own within two to six days. Patients should be recommended an \u003Cstrong\u003Eeye shield\u003C/strong\u003E to protect the eye from further damage. Patients may also be advised to elevate the head of the bed in order to help in the clearance of the hyphaema. In particular, patients should be evaluated for nausea or vomiting since nausea may be an indicator of elevated intraocular pressure. Moreover, vomiting may increase the intraocular pressure further. Patients who also have features of nausea or vomiting should be given antiemetics (eg \u003Cstrong\u003Etropisetron\u003C/strong\u003E). This patient does not have nausea or vomiting and does not need any antiemetic at this moment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECycloplegic drugs (eg, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecyclopentolate\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eatropine\u003C/strong\u003E) may be prescribed after ophthalmologic evaluation. In the interim, only an eye shield should be recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETopical beta-blockers (eg, \u003Cstrong\u003Etimolol\u003C/strong\u003E) may be beneficial in patients with elevated intraocular pressure, provided they are not asthmatic, as beta-blockers can induce an asthmatic attack, even status asthmatica. However, this decision should be made after an ophthalmologic evaluation. Besides, this patient does not have features suggesting elevated intraocular pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An ophthalmological opinion should always be sought in any eye injury that results in an hyphaema."],"references":["Gharaibeh A, Savage HI, Scherer RW, Goldberg MF, Lindsley K. Medical interventions for traumatic hyphema. Cochrane Database Syst Rev. 2013;12(12):CD005431. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6353164/pdf/CD005431.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28254"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2401"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"28254","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/28254"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-03-08T19:13:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-03-08T19:13:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2401"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"43264"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc41","name":"Ophthalmology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu